{
  "texts": [
    "The twisting homomorphism maps the generator of Z ≃ π 1 (S 1) to the map x → -x.Example 2.4 (Lie group quotients).",
    "Generalising the previous example, let G = R ⋉ θ N be a semidirect product of Lie groups defined by a homomorphism θ: R → Aut(N).",
    "There is a properly discontinuous action of Z on G given by k• (t, n) = (t + 2πk, θ(2πk)n), thus M:= G/Z is a smooth manifold.",
    "The projection G → G/N ≃ R induces a well-defined submersion π: M → S 1, [(t, n)] M → [t] R/Z.Then M is a twisted principal N-bundle, with twisting homomorphism ρ:π 1 (S 1) ≃ Z → Aut(N), ρ(k) = θ(2πk).",
    "The canonical vertical connections.A key property of twisted principal bundles is the existence of canonically-defined affine connections ∇ V,b on the tangent bundle of each fibre M b, that depend smoothly on b ∈ B, and are flat and with parallel torsion."
  ]
}